commentBody:
@SShah

I've got a lawn that needs mowing.  
You could do that.

@NovelaMaven

Don't.

Enjoy your solve and your magic beans, and don't worry about what anyone else thinks of the puzzle.

@Weak

That was my last entry, changing that "t" to a "g".

I was lucky to find it.

@Weak

That clue "out" for the entry NOT IN? I'm so glad you brought it up!

It got a huge guffaw out of me. Loved it!

@Anonymous

I didn’t assess the puzzle’s difficulty. I just said it was good and fair. Saturday puzzles will, and should, vary in difficulty.  And that variance frequently elicits 10PM ET snark. 

I am typically a morning solver, but happened to get this one done on Friday night. Did I solve it faster than usual? Sure. But I still enjoyed doing so.

@Red Carpet

The answer to that is--never enough!! 

🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩🦩

@HeathieJ
okay... in Fire Island Pines (in the town of Brookhaven) there's a house that has major flamingo energy. They have a Facebook page and are on Instagram. Apparently the current installation is World Cup themed. Here's the Insta:

<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/DZqQjEeP5zX" target="_blank">https://www.instagram.com/p/DZqQjEeP5zX</a>/

@HeathieJ
there were zero other random names as perfect.
wishing you strength and forbearance in difficult times.

@dutchiris
The young Charles Dance, be still my heart. The entire cast was terrific. 
I was pretty young when I read the books and was still in the stage of just devouring anything I was reading.

@Mean Old Lady
As books usually do.  Charles Dance played a villain in season or two? of  Game of Thrones.
Also, if you've never seen the adaptation of Bleak House starring him and Gillian Anderson, it's worth hunting down.

@Scott
with a blank canvas I totally expected it to be someone who went on to become a major director. Crosses disabused me of that notion.

In the US Magical Mystery Tour is generally viewed as a good album soundtrack to a terribly flawed film. In the UK apparently the viewing was par for the course for Boxing Day fare. I will admit that I'm ready to hear it again today, and don't need to see it again at present. ;)

@jennie

Ten o‘clockers…I like that!

Proud to be one, though I’m solving in the morning these days. Will be glad to return to nighttime solving on Monday.

@Joy Harkin
That would likely have been clued Australian.
But I tried it too.

@Mean Old Lady
The term 'gal pal' has no equivalent that I've ever heard of. The word gal is not really used. I find the term gal pal rather weird (so American ...) and I would just say 'friend' as it would be obvious from the context if it was male or female. 
If anyone mentioned Galentine's Day I would mime throwing up and expect my friends to do the same!

@Nick

I’m with Barry. If you can’t solve for the third letter of RA_ when clued as [British ___ (colonial rule of India)] then I don’t know what to tell you. That’s a fairly basic historical fact that would be considered by many of us as part of the general knowledge expected for a Saturday crossword. 

Sorry if that sounds snobbish and elitist, but this is a terrific illustration of the whole point some of us are making about Saturday crosswords.

@Anonymous

But I want constructors to show off how smart they are!

Who wants a puzzle constructed by a dull person?

@ad absurdum

For some reason my reply keeps getting emu’d but I’ll try again:

I’m sure he had a good head on his shoulders, and if he didn’t he could always get a new one

@Anonymous I have been completing one corresponding day from the archives (at least ten or so years back), and you are 100% correct. On Friday and Saturday I often simply cannot complete those puzzles because they are so much more difficult. For anyone who hasn't, I also encourage you to test this out.

There is simply no way to say the puzzles now are of the same difficulty if you do this. Maybe people like the easier puzzles. But it really makes me sad to see the difference. Puzzles are supposed to be hard; a lot of people should not be able to solve them. If that makes someone upset...oh well. 

I would also love for the editors to actually acknowledge this and hear them say whatever their rationale is. It feels a bit like gaslighting to just act as though the puzzles are the same and we're just getting so much better at them or soemthing.

@Anonymous
I'm back. Had to walk away from that Friday puzzle for awhile and come back to it. Nothing that comes within my allowable cheat rules (which are extensive) was sufficient. 

Finally tried a different three letter entry at the top and then the whole thing fell. Hey, when the whole thing falls at once after that kind of struggle, it feels really good!

@Endall

We are in violent agreement here. And to echo something that you and one other commenter said in another thread, perhaps *the* key underlying difference between puzzles from 10+ years ago and an overwhelming majority of the ones from the last few years is an unwillingness to publish puzzles that much/most of the subscriber base will be unable to complete.

I also find this change very disappointing, but I suspect it will ultimately come back to bite them — i assume they’ve extracted lots of value from the “NYT Crossword” brand these last few years, but we’ll see how long they can keep that going, as they continue to dilute the cachet of that very brand in the process.

@Andrzej

Welcome back. 

So, without a fence, "Zejdź z mojego trawnika!" is not appropriate?  :)

@Barry Ancona

No, we don't. Of course, bumper stickers exist over here, too, but their variety is very limited (the Christian fish, sport team logo, baby on board, some cringey anti-traffic-law slogan). My wife and I found American bumper stickers fascinating. We keep a diary on holiday, and both our American vacations it featured a "Bumper sticker of the day" section.

I've never seen a school bumper sticker over here - I don't think our schools even make those. I know my faculty sure does not.

@Andrzej
Well, they might have withheld some of the bumper stickers I would have shared. So there is that.

For sardonic humor today, I'm forced to rely on the NYT front page. But it has enough. You may rest.

@Andrzej

Top ten signs you might be a lawyer...

'Sup, dude?

@Bryan
Also a bumper sticker.

And another one, "Stop continental drift!"

@Liz M
Not just you.
Nailed some long phrases, lots of easy short crosses and T/W time.

@Jeff Z

LEGO TAT MAM: she who applies tattoos to LEGO creatures. Also called a LEGO TAT ARTISTE.

(Please do not look this up until I have time to create a Wiki page for it!)

@Seth

Your 8-minute is thirty other solvers' 60 minutes. Why do so many people think it's all about them? Unless you were asked to solve in advance and submit your finish time, no one knows how fast it will take any single person to finish a puzzle. 

Going back to solving now.

@Nancy
Very nicely said. I also can't remember an easier Saturday.

And yes, I think that may be my favorite cartoon of all time.

@Lynn
Your BAdMAN comment -- still laughing!   
And I didn't have Legos as a kid either- but that was the '50's...

@DocP

I'm very saddened to hear and can't imagine any good reason for your post to have been taken down.
It was a lovely tribute. Thank you for sharing Foxy's story with us.

@Mary

Since February? Perhaps the puzzles have gotten a little tougher since then on average — as I recall, February was kind of the peak of “NYT tries to poach USA Today puzzlers” (the only reason I have any such recollection is due to the Valentine’s day Saturday puzzle, on which I remember getting most of the long entries instantly, without any crosses at all).

But the talk about declining puzzle difficulty is more about the last ~few years, in contrast to the preceding couple/few decades (i.e. the Shortz golden age).

@Mark

Not sure if you're asking for clarity, but "DEES" is the answer because the word "diamond" starts and ends with a D. So, DEES are the edges of the word. The clue is given a question mark to indicate you need to think of it in a punny or stretchy way.

(Question marks are presented more rarely on a Saturday; it's usually left to the solver to figure out the clue is a stretch or a dad joke.)

@Mark
As I learned uncomfortably when playing against a Scrabble expert, each letter does, indeed, have an accepted dictionary spelling for its name. For example, the name of the letter H is "aitch." My foe pulled out his dictionary to prove it to me. Here is an online one:
<a href="https://www.dictionary.com/articles/how-to-spell-letters" target="_blank">https://www.dictionary.com/articles/how-to-spell-letters</a>

@Mark

Solver hint:  If the clue doesn't make a lick of sense, try considering that the clue is for the structure of the word itself.

For example LONGIS (long i's) might be the answer for [A pair in highlights].

@Francis

I'm one of the OGs, and I can confirm, my first year or so doing the NYT I had to look things up for most of the week, and my first few Saturday solves were indeed on the easier side.

Stick it out, and it will get easier!
